1. **Thesis**: Suffering and evil in the world are not objective realities imposed on us, but subjective experiences we choose within an all-encompassing divine creation. Since God creates all possibilities, our personal reality—including pain—is a matter of individual perspective and choice. We are here, experiencing this, because we have chosen to be.

2. **Agreement**: I agree in principle—the text compellingly reframes suffering as a chosen lens within an infinite possibility space, emphasizing agency and the constructed nature of subjective reality. However, this risks minimizing real-world suffering; while perception shapes experience, systemic harm exists intersubjectively and demands compassionate response, not just philosophical detachment.

3. **Poem**:

> If God is all, and all is choice,  
> Why does the hurting heart rejoice?  
> Not in the wound, but in the light—  
> You chose the stage, the dark, the sight.  
>  
> The tiger’s tooth, the whispered pain,  
> Are shadows you let fall like rain.  
> Step out? The door is never locked—  
> You’re holding keys you’ve long forgot.  
>  
> So breathe the world you came to know:  
> The ache, the wonder, high, and low.  
> For every tear was yours to pour—  
> And every dawn, your open door. [end of text]


